      "type": "answer",
      "text": "**Root‑Cause Analysis (Enterprise RCA)**  \nWHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR (stop code 0x124) is a hardware‑level crash. Windows detected a fault it could not correct, usually from:\n\n1. **Overheating** – CPU/GPU temps exceeding safe limits.  \n2. **Unstable overclocking** – CPU/RAM/GPU pushed beyond stock specs.  \n3. **Faulty hardware** – failing RAM, CPU, SSD, GPU, or motherboard.  \n4. **Power‑delivery issues** – weak or failing PSU.  \n5. **BIOS/UEFI bugs** – outdated firmware or incorrect settings.  \n6. **Driver conflicts** – especially chipset, storage, or GPU drivers.\n\nMultiple occurrences yesterday point to a persistent instability. Check **Event Viewer → System → Source: WHEA‑Logger** to see which component reported the error.\n\n**Fixability Score (iFixit)**  \n- **Desktop PC**: 8/10 (modular, parts easily replaceable).  \n- **Laptop**: 5–7/10 (depends on model; some are glued/soldered).  \nProvide your exact model for a precise score.\n\n**Reliability of Diagnosis**  \nThe error is a reliable indicator of hardware/firmware instability. If the cause is overheating or unstable settings, the fix is reliable. If a component is failing, replacement may be needed.\n\n**Temperature Monitoring (Safe, No Stress Test)**  \nYou can monitor temps without stressing components:\n\n**PowerShell (run as Admin)**  \n```powershell\nGet-WmiObject MSAcpi_ThermalZoneTemperature -Namespace \"root/wmi\" |\n  ForEach-Object { ($_.CurrentTemperature/10 - 273.15).ToString(\"N1\") + \" °C\" }\n```\nIf “Access denied,” run PowerShell as Administrator.\n\n**Python (install `psutil`)**  \n```python\nimport psutil\ntemps = psutil.sensors_temperatures()\nif 'coretemp' in temps:\n    for temp in temps['coretemp']:\n        print(f\"{temp.label}: {temp.current}°C\")\nelse:\n    print(\"Temperature sensors not available.\")\n```\nInstall psutil: `pip install psutil`.\n\n**Next Steps**  \n1. Open Event Viewer, filter for WHEA‑Logger, note the faulting component.  \n2. Run the temperature checks above; ensure CPU stays below 80°C under normal load.  \n3. If overclocked, revert to stock settings in BIOS.  \n4. Update BIOS/UEFI and chipset/GPU drivers.  \n5. If errors persist, run a memory test (Windows Memory Diagnostic) and check SSD health.\n\nProceed with these diagnostics before considering hardware replacement.",
      "timestamp": 1783146398095
